naive bayes penguins

Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(bayesrules)
library(janitor)
library(e1071)
options(scipen = 99)

Story

Well start our naive Bayes classification with just a single penguin. Suppose an Antarctic researcher comes across a penguin that weighs less than 4200g with a 195mm-long flipper and 50mm-long bill. Our goal is to help this researcher identify the species of this penguin, Adelie, Chinstrap, or Gentoo.

Lets Plot!

Make a visualization that will help the researcher determine the species based on the characteristics described above

data(penguins_bayes)
penguins <- penguins_bayes
ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = above_average_weight, fill = species)) +
  geom_bar()

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(bill_length_mm, flipper_length_mm, color = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  facet_grid(~species)

Our old bayesian ways

P(B|A) P(Chinstrap | below average weight) = 31%

penguins %>%
  tabyl(above_average_weight, species) %>% 
  adorn_percentages("row")
##  above_average_weight    Adelie  Chinstrap     Gentoo

Naive Bayes Classification!

naive_model_hints <- naiveBayes(species ~ flipper_length_mm + bill_length_mm + above_average_weight, data = penguins)

Our Penguin

our_penguin <- data.frame(bill_length_mm = 50, flipper_length_mm = 195, above_average_weight = "no")

ask our model what species our penguin is

predict(naive_model_hints, newdata = our_penguin, type = "raw")
##            Adelie Chinstrap       Gentoo
## [1,] 0.0003219805 0.9994165 0.0002615187

Test our model for accuracy with confusion matrix

penguins <- penguins %>% 
  mutate(predicted_species = predict(naive_model_hints, newdata = .))
penguins %>% 
  tabyl(species, predicted_species) %>% 
  adorn_percentages("row") %>% 
  adorn_pct_formatting(digits = 2) %>% 
  adorn_ns
